
FACADE PATTERN
==============
The Facade Design Pattern is a structural design pattern that provides a single, simplified interface to a complex subsystem. Instead of forcing clients to coordinate many moving parts, a facade hides the internal complexity and exposes a clean, easy-to-use entry point.
“Why do we need a Facade?”
Say:
Facade is used to hide system complexity and provide a single
entry point for the client, reducing coupling and simplifying usage.


1. DEFINITION
-------------
Facade Pattern provides a simplified unified interface
to a complex subsystem.

It acts as a SINGLE ENTRY POINT for the system.

=================================================

2. INTENT
----------
✔ Simplify complex subsystem usage
✔ Reduce client-subsystem coupling
✔ Provide easy-to-use API

=================================================

3. REAL-WORLD ANALOGY
---------------------
- Hotel reception (you don’t deal with departments directly)
- Mobile banking app (hides internal banking systems)
- Uber app (hides driver, routing, payment complexity)

=================================================

4. PROBLEM WITHOUT FACADE
-------------------------
- Client interacts with multiple subsystems directly
- High coupling
- Code becomes complex
- Hard to maintain and change

=================================================

5. SOLUTION
-----------
Facade provides a single class that internally manages
multiple subsystem calls.

Client → Facade → Subsystems

=================================================

6. KEY IDEA
-----------
Facade = “Front door to the system”

It does NOT change subsystem logic,
only simplifies usage.

=================================================

7. BENEFITS
-----------
✔ Reduces complexity
✔ Reduces coupling
✔ Improves readability
✔ Centralized control

=================================================

8. DRAWBACKS
------------
❌ Can become a god class if overloaded
❌ May hide useful subsystem functionality

=================================================


9. ONE-LINE DEFINITION
----------------------
Facade Pattern provides a unified interface to a set of subsystems to simplify their usage.

=================================================

10. MEMORY TRICK
---------------
Facade = "Front desk / entry point of system"

Facade vs Adapter
Facade:
- Simplifies a system
- Multiple subsystems → one interface

Adapter:
- Converts one interface to another
- Compatibility problem solving



#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

// =====================
// SUBSYSTEMS
// =====================

class PaymentGateway {
public:
    void processPayment() {
        cout << "Payment processed." << endl;
    }
};

class Inventory {
public:
    void checkStock() {
        cout << "Inventory checked." << endl;
    }
};

class InvoiceSystem {
public:
    void generateInvoice() {
        cout << "Invoice generated." << endl;
    }
};

class EmailService {
public:
    void sendConfirmationEmail() {
        cout << "Email sent." << endl;
    }
};

// =====================
// FACADE
// =====================

class OrderFacade {
private:
    PaymentGateway payment;
    Inventory inventory;
    InvoiceSystem invoice;
    EmailService email;

public:
    void placeOrder() {
        inventory.checkStock();
        payment.processPayment();
        invoice.generateInvoice();
        email.sendConfirmationEmail();

        cout << "Order placed successfully!" << endl;
    }
};

// =====================
// CLIENT
// =====================

int main() {
    OrderFacade order;

    order.placeOrder();

    return 0;
}


Inventory checked.
Payment processed.
Invoice generated.
Email sent.
Order placed successfully!

1. The Problem: Deployment Complexity
Let's say you're building a deployment automation tool for your development team.

On the surface, deploying an application may seem like a straightforward task, but in reality, it involves a sequence of coordinated, error-prone steps:

Pull the latest code from a Git repository
Build the project using a tool like Maven or Gradle
Run automated tests (unit, integration, maybe end-to-end)
Deploy the build artifact to a production environment
Each of these steps might be handled by a separate module or class, each with its own specific API and configuration.

Client Code Without Facade
Without a facade, the client must directly interact with each subsystem, knowing exactly which methods to call and in what order.

The client is tightly coupled to every subsystem

Implementing the Facade
The DeploymentFacade class serves as a single, unified interface to the complex set of operations involved in application deployment.

Internally, it holds references to the core building blocks of the deployment pipeline:

VersionControlSystem - Fetches the latest code from a Git branch
BuildSystem - Compiles the code and generates the deployable artifact
TestingFramework - Runs automated tests (unit, integration)
DeploymentTarget - Transfers the artifact and activates it on the target server
